      "side": 1,
      "message": "There are two different strategies in use right now:\n- Most code that knows it\u0027s making a long-lived effect will cache it after creation. All of the internal effects used by the GPU backend, for example, use function-static variables to hold the effect. Chrome\u0027s color conversion code in the compositor uses a map to hold the effects, keyed by the source and dest color spaces, etc.\n- In some situations, the caller *can\u0027t* do this. The big one is deserialization. For that, there\u0027s a private factory \"SkMakeCachedRuntimeEffect\". That uses the SkSL as a key, and stores the parsed effects in an LRU cache.\n- If you simply call SkRuntimeEffect::Make, however, it will be just as slow the second time as it was the first...",
